<h2>What Are The Qualities Of The Best Cat Litter Box?</h2>
<p><img decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-9930" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/ideal-cat-litter-box.png" alt="ideal cat litter box" width="700" height="402" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/ideal-cat-litter-box.png 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/ideal-cat-litter-box-600x345.png 600w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/ideal-cat-litter-box-624x358.png 624w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /></p>
<p>The best cat litter boxes satisfy your catâ€™s needs in a variety of ways. Letâ€™s take a closer look at what the best cat litter boxes do that mediocre ones donâ€™t.</p>
<h3>The best cat litter box gives your cat space.</h3>
<p>Litter boxes are primarily designed with human comfort in mind. That means that theyâ€™re usually small and compact enough to fit in a small room.</p>
<p>As a result, the average litter box leaves your catâ€™s head and tail over the edge. Imagine how it feels to use a litter box with barely enough room to move around in, forcing you to step in your own waste. For a creature as hygiene-conscious as a cat, this is a foul situation.</p>
<p>General cat care wisdom says that cats should use litter boxes that are at least as wide as they are long, from the nose tip to the base of their tail. For example, if your cat is 15â€ long from nose tip to the base of their tail, she will need a litter box thatâ€™s at least 15â€ wide and 22.5â€ long.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/danielle-page-046b2546/">Dr. Danielle (Elly) Page BVSc, BCom</a> tells us that &#8220;the best type of litter box is the plain plastic variety with tall sides and the largest you can buy.&#8221;</p>
<p><img decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-9931" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/cat-litter-space.png" alt="cat litter space" width="700" height="394" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/cat-litter-space.png 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/cat-litter-space-600x338.png 600w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/cat-litter-space-624x351.png 624w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /></p>
<h3>The best cat litter boxes have high sides.</h3>
<p>Small litter boxes struggle to keep litter where it belongs. A little tracking and scattering are inevitable, but low-sided litter boxes have more problems than most. Think about choosing a high-sided litter box made specifically with litter scattering in mind.</p>
<p>Remember that some cats, especially females, spray urine on the sides and over the edges of the litter box. If your litter box has low sides, itâ€™s likely that the urine will go over the edge and onto the floor. High sides help to keep everything inside of the box.</p>
<h3>The litter box must also be easy for your cat to access.</h3>
<p>A running start shouldnâ€™t be a part of your catâ€™s litter box entry approach. Kittens and senior cats are particularly prone to problems accessing a litter box with high sides, so choose boxes with a lowered entrance for easy access.</p>
<h3>Every litter box needs to be cleaned at least once a day. The best litter boxes make the chore easier.</h3>
<p>Choose litter boxes with smooth inner surfaces that make scooping simple. Avoid boxes with hard-to-clean designs, including inside curves, ridges, and valleys. All of these features collect waste and make your job more challenging. Avoid litter boxes with square corners, as well â€“ these are also difficult to clean out completely. Some litter boxes have non-stick and antimicrobial coatings, which help to manage odors.</p>
<h2>Types of Litter Boxes</h2>
<p><img decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-9932" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/types-of-cat-litter-boxes.png" alt="types of cat litter boxes" width="700" height="280" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/types-of-cat-litter-boxes.png 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/types-of-cat-litter-boxes-600x240.png 600w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/types-of-cat-litter-boxes-624x250.png 624w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /></p>
<p>The litter box is a straightforward product â€“ but that doesnâ€™t mean you donâ€™t have options. The litter box selection ranges from nondescript plastic pans to alien-looking automatic sifting machines. Letâ€™s take a closer look.</p>
<h3>Sifting Cat Litter Boxes</h3>
<p>Sifting litter boxes are the less technologically-advanced cousin of the automatic litter box. Although they donâ€™t do all of the cleaning for you, sifting litter boxes eliminate the need to scoop out the box â€“ they essentially scoop themselves.</p>
<p>These litter boxes work best with clumping litter since this type separates into dirty clumps and clean granules. Theyâ€™re also the best choice for people using pine pellet litter, which breaks down to sawdust after it comes into contact with moisture. The sifter separates the used dust from the fresh pellets, extending the life of the litter.</p>
<h3>Uncovered Cat Litter Boxes</h3>
<p>Over the course of about 70 years of commercial litter box evolution, the litter box has seen a few technological advances, but the standard plastic litter pan still reigns supreme. Uncovered litter boxes are usually cheap and easy to find in stores.</p>
<p>This is the classic litter box. Itâ€™s just a pan that holds your catâ€™s litter. Itâ€™s easy to clean, easy to access, and a popular choice among all types of cat guardians. Cats naturally want to keep an eye out for threats while they use the litter box, and uncovered boxes make area surveillance easy.</p>
<p>For these reasons, uncovered litter boxes are the type most often recommended by vets and behaviorists. <a href="https://www.trendingbreeds.com/about/">Dr. Amanda Takiguchi, DVM</a>Â says that &#8220;from (her) experience,&#8230;get a litter box with no topâ€¦ open tray,&#8221; adding that she &#8220;just got a couple of new ones from Amazon that have really high sides and a lower spot in front for the cat to enter.&#8221;</p>
<h3>Covered Cat Litter Boxes</h3>
<p>Covered cat litter boxes capture the smell inside of a litter chamber, minimizing the amount of waste odor that spreads through your home. In addition to minimizing odor, covered litter boxes help to curb litter scattering. Because the hood disguises the functional part of the litter box, theyâ€™re popular among people who want to minimize the appearance of a litter box in their home.</p>
<p>Although human interests are the primary reason people opt for using a covered litter box, sometimes misconceptions about feline preferences also play a role in their use. Itâ€™s easy to assume that because people appreciate seclusion while using their bathrooms, cats want the same privacy. Being trapped in the litter box doesnâ€™t make cats safe â€“ it makes them vulnerable.</p>
<p>The covered cat litter box has also been criticized for encouraging laziness. Critics say they make cat guardians ignorant of waste accumulation. In addition to hiding the problem, covered litter boxes trap smells inside a small space. Itâ€™s a situation sometimes compared to a public portable bathroom â€“ an unclean stench chamber. For an animal with an acute sense of smell and a love of good hygiene, this could be intolerable.</p>
<p>All this being said, many cats happily use covered litter boxes throughout their lives.Â <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23103684/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-at-href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23103684/">This study showed</a>Â that cats demonstrated no preference for open or covered litter boxes.</p>
<p>And <a href="https://buttercrossvets.co.uk/about-us/meet-the-team/surgeons/">Dr. Alex Crow</a>,Â  a practicing vet at the Buttercross Veterinary Centre in Nottinghamshire, England, agrees that the difference between covered and uncovered litter boxes is not as big as you might initially think.</p>
<p>He says that &#8220;some people might say there is a major difference between open and closed litter boxes, but this is not necessarily true. Most cats simply want a clean place to use the bathroom, and the hood is only really convenient if you donâ€™t want other animals or children to get into it. The hood can help with the amount of litter dust in your home which might be something you want to consider.&#8221;</p>
<p>If you clean out the box once a day or more, a covered cat litter box can be an aesthetically superior alternative to the traditional open litter tray.</p>
<h3>Automatic or Self-Cleaning Cat Litter Boxes</h3>
<p>Automatic or self-cleaning litter boxes are a good fit for people who hate the process of cleaning out the litter box manually. Typically, this type of litter box has a sensor that detects the presence of a cat. After your cat uses the litter box, a sifting or raking mechanism automatically separates clean from dirty litter. The waste then enters a storage drawer, where it remains until youâ€™re ready to discard it.</p>
<p>Automatic litter boxes cost more than less advanced products, and they come with an increased risk of malfunctions, but theyâ€™re a good investment for someone with a busy schedule or a procrastination streak.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/carencarneydvm/">Dr. Caren Carney, DVM</a>, recommends automatic litter boxes for picky cats with strong constitutions. She says that &#8220;automatic litter boxes are good for the picky cat that wants a pristine box all the time because the box is always clean. But they can be noisy, so some cats may be scared of them. Many of the automatic ones require an extra layer of upkeep for the owner, including cleaning parts, and a risk of a big mess in the case of malfunction.&#8221;</p>
<h3>Top Entry Cat Litter Boxes</h3>
<p>Visually, top entry boxes are one of the most chic styles available. Instead of walking into the litter box from an entrance at the front or sides of the box, your cat drops down into the litter through an entrance hole on the top. This type of litter box is harder for cats to access, so itâ€™s not a great choice for cats with mobility issues. Itâ€™s also speculated that this type of litter boxÂ <a href="https://catinfo.org/the-litter-box-from-your-cats-point-of-view/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-at-href="https://catinfo.org/the-litter-box-from-your-cats-point-of-view/">may place undue stress</a> on catsâ€™ joints.</p>
<h2>Remember your cat&#8217;s unique needs.</h2>
<p>Veterinarian <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/chyrle-bonk-999b99209?miniProfileUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_miniProfile%3AACoAADUI70UBT5ojDlba7mts3tNynM8QXbWAiUQ&amp;lipi=urn%3Ali%3Apage%3Ad_flagship3_search_srp_all%3BHhq8lVsJQG6Q%2BGLbbr%2BfIA%3D%3D">Dr. Chyrle Bonk, DVM</a> emphasizes that your cat&#8217;s needs come first, saying that &#8220;no matter how great a litter box may be, itâ€™s completely worthless if your kitty doesnâ€™t like it. Some important considerations to keep in mind are whether or not your cat has any health issues.Â Things like arthritis can make it hard to climb into a tall-sided litter box and make one with low sides or a lower door the best option. Some cats may prefer the privacy of a covered litter box, while others will get scared by one. Automatic litter boxes may frighten some cats, yet be the best choice for those fastidious ones.&#8221;</p>
<div itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">
<h2 class="cliverse-faq-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Whatâ€™s the best cat litter box for odor control?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>If your catâ€™s litter box has an odor problem, look at yourself first. Ensure that youâ€™ve been cleaning out the box at least once a day. If a diligent cleaning routine leaves the litter box still smelling foul, choosing a new litter box could help.</p>
<p>Some litter boxes have non-stick and antimicrobial coatings that help to minimize the amount of waste that sticks to their inside surfaces. These coatings also help to minimize the growth of odor-causing bacteria. Others feature carbon filters that capture odors before they can enter the room.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Do cats prefer open or closed litter boxes?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Every cat has their own unique preferences in terms of litter boxes, but there are some benefits to choosing an enclosed versus an open litter box.</p>
<p>Enclosed litter boxes provide a higher degree of privacy, with the added benefit of containing odor and litter scatter better than an open box. The downside is some cats may find an enclosed box too cramped. Large breeds in particular may be more comfortable in an open litter box.</p>
<p>Though there are pros and cons for each option, limited research suggests most cats donâ€™t really have a preference when it comes to open or closed litter boxes. Researchers at the Ross University School of Veterinary MedicineÂ <a href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/1098612X12465606" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-at-href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/1098612X12465606">completed a study in 2012</a>Â that revealed that 70% of cats showed no preference for one kind of litter box over the other.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Whatâ€™s the best cat litter box for large cats?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>If you own a super-sized Maine Coon or massive Chausie, it can be a struggle to find an adequate litter box. Litter boxes are usually undersized for average cats, and the search is even more challenging for a large cat.</p>
<p>Covered litter boxes are out of the question forÂ <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/large-cat-breeds" target="_blank" rel="noopener">large cats</a>. While even small uncovered litter boxes allow your cat to extend their head and tail over the edges, a covered litter box has restrictive side walls that make your cat feel cramped. Look for big, sturdy uncovered boxes.</p>
<p>Because huge litter boxes are rare, many large cat guardians choose toÂ <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n_KBWzHvNn4" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-at-href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n_KBWzHvNn4">make their own</a>Â litter boxes or use plastic storage containers instead.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Whatâ€™s the best litter box for multiple cats?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>In a multiple cat home, the litter box has to handle increased box activity while also facilitating healthy relationships.</p>
<p>The standard recommendation is that you install as many litter boxes as you have cats, plus one. One cat needs two litter boxes and twelve cats need thirteen. In addition to accommodating your multiple cats with numerous litter boxes, choose sizable boxes that can handle heavy use. A big cat family creates plenty of waste, and it takes large litter boxes to handle that.</p>
<p>Remember that multiple cat households have a uniquely feline social hierarchy. As a central part of daily life, the litter box can get involved in territorial spats and social dominance games. A dominant cat may block a submissive family member inside of the litter box, forcing them to stand in their own waste. This is a frightening and humiliating experience and can send the conflict on a downward spiral.</p>
<p>For this reason, avoid placing your litter box in a corner and donâ€™t use covered boxes in a multiple cat home.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Whatâ€™s the best cat litter box to keep dogs out?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Some dogs love eating smelly little cat treats from the litter box.</p>
<p>This is at once disgusting to watch, unsanitary, and potentially dangerous. Choosing the right box can prevent your dog from invading the litter box. Several designs can help to keep your dog out of the litter box. One is a top entry box, which keeps small dogs from accessing the waste area. Other boxes have both an inner and outer entry, preventing larger dogs from probing into the box.</p>
<p>If you donâ€™t want to give your cat a covered litter box, there are other options for keeping your dog out. If your cat is agile and comfortable jumping, take advantage of their vertical mobility and put the litter box on a counter or large shelf that your dog canâ€™t access.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Whatâ€™s the best cat litter box for small apartments?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Having a small home doesnâ€™t mean you need to cut back on litter box space. Instead of saving space by choosing a small box, choose one that can multitask.</p>
<p>Litter box furniture enclosures double as storage areas and shelving, allowing you to maximize your space. Because these pieces make functional decorative accents, they have more placement options than the average litter box.</p>
<p>While itâ€™s usually a good idea to place your litter box in the bathroom, laundry room, or other discreet area, multifunctional boxes can go almost anywhere. Regardless of how limited your space is, try to place the litter box in a low-traffic area where your cat will have a stress-free elimination experience.</p>
</div>
